WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.936 --> 00:00:03.440
GINGER THOMPSON: Hi, everybody.

00:00:03.440 --> 00:00:07.010
Thank you for your patience
with us as we get started.

00:00:07.010 --> 00:00:08.160
My name is Ginger Thompson.

00:00:08.160 --> 00:00:11.300
I'm with Lewa Wildlife
Conservancy here in the US,

00:00:11.300 --> 00:00:13.230
and I'm the executive director.

00:00:13.230 --> 00:00:16.379
I'm here with my
colleagues Geoffrey Chege,

00:00:16.379 --> 00:00:20.380
who's our chief conservation
officer, who flew in from Kenya

00:00:20.380 --> 00:00:24.550
a couple of days ago,
and John Battelle, who's

00:00:24.550 --> 00:00:26.370
on our US board
and actually about

00:00:26.370 --> 00:00:29.980
to become vice president
of our US board.

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:33.950
We're here to talk to you today
about Lewa Wildlife Conservancy

00:00:33.950 --> 00:00:38.790
and really a much bigger
movement that we're the engine

00:00:38.790 --> 00:00:42.600
room for in Northern
Kenya in an effort

00:00:42.600 --> 00:00:46.390
to take a very
large area of land

00:00:46.390 --> 00:00:49.490
and put it into
conservation management,

00:00:49.490 --> 00:00:52.250
conservation that's
actually community centric.

00:00:52.250 --> 00:00:56.970
So we are a community
conservation organization.

00:00:56.970 --> 00:00:59.720
We're going to play a video
for you so you get a sense

00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:03.060
and a feel of the place itself.

00:01:03.060 --> 00:01:06.530
But following our
conversation today,

00:01:06.530 --> 00:01:08.410
there are a few
things that we think

00:01:08.410 --> 00:01:14.580
it's important to step away
with from our tech talk here.

00:01:14.580 --> 00:01:21.010
The first is that Lewa is
a small but very prominent

00:01:21.010 --> 00:01:23.390
organization in the
conservation field,

00:01:23.390 --> 00:01:27.230
in community conservation, and
particularly in East Africa.

00:01:27.230 --> 00:01:31.560
We've become a model for a lot
of other public and private

00:01:31.560 --> 00:01:35.700
organizations attempting
to preserve wildlife

00:01:35.700 --> 00:01:39.280
by working with
communities to do so.

00:01:39.280 --> 00:01:41.330
It's got a big vision.

00:01:41.330 --> 00:01:43.760
It's got a great team.

00:01:43.760 --> 00:01:47.670
And we've had financial
efficacy for many, many years.

00:01:47.670 --> 00:01:49.390
So there's lots to
be said about Lewa,

00:01:49.390 --> 00:01:51.500
and you'll hear more about us.

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:54.500
We have an enormous
opportunity today

00:01:54.500 --> 00:01:57.760
to do something that really
hasn't been done anywhere,

00:01:57.760 --> 00:02:04.740
which is to create a massive
wildlife area in Africa that

00:02:04.740 --> 00:02:09.210
can sustain all the iconic
species that we've talked

00:02:09.210 --> 00:02:14.240
about over years in Africa,
but also sustain livelihoods

00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:16.980
of people who are pastoralists
who have worked and lived

00:02:16.980 --> 00:02:21.790
with animals, this wildlife,
for generations and millennia,

00:02:21.790 --> 00:02:22.880
really.

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:28.110
And that opportunity is unique
to this area of Northern Kenya.

00:02:28.110 --> 00:02:31.250
Finally, we have a very
critical issue going on,

00:02:31.250 --> 00:02:34.500
which I'm sure you've all read
much about, which is poaching.

00:02:34.500 --> 00:02:39.370
Poaching has reduced the
numbers of elephants, and rhino,

00:02:39.370 --> 00:02:45.160
and big cats, and wild
dogs extraordinarily

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:47.940
in the past 10 to 15 years.

00:02:47.940 --> 00:02:50.670
The demand for ivory, the
demand for rhino horn,

00:02:50.670 --> 00:02:55.580
the demand for pelts, the
demand for all sorts of organs

00:02:55.580 --> 00:02:57.620
has grown so dramatically.

00:02:57.620 --> 00:03:01.240
And it's really been taken
up by criminal gangs that

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:05.620
are using international
ports to move goods to raise

00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:07.770
lots of money for
terrorist activities,

00:03:07.770 --> 00:03:09.330
et cetera, et cetera.

00:03:09.330 --> 00:03:11.550
That single issue
of poaching has

00:03:11.550 --> 00:03:14.320
reduced populations
of elephant and rhino

00:03:14.320 --> 00:03:18.020
from the millions
down to the thousands.

00:03:18.020 --> 00:03:23.710
So we need help in
keeping this all growing

00:03:23.710 --> 00:03:26.780
and restoring wildlife to this
wonderful area of Northern

00:03:26.780 --> 00:03:27.640
Kenya.

00:03:27.640 --> 00:03:32.190
And that's what we're
here to talk to you about.

00:03:32.190 --> 00:03:36.980
Community and conservation
are symbiotic.

00:03:36.980 --> 00:03:39.940
You can't conserve
wildlife areas

00:03:39.940 --> 00:03:43.880
without the people
involved in doing so.

00:03:43.880 --> 00:03:45.260
It's a human issue.

00:03:45.260 --> 00:03:46.840
It's not a wildlife issue.

00:03:46.840 --> 00:03:48.060
It's not a habitat issue.

00:03:48.060 --> 00:03:50.190
It's a human issue,
conservation.

00:03:50.190 --> 00:03:52.450
So the great lessons
and the billions

00:03:52.450 --> 00:03:55.480
of dollars that were spent in
conservation over the last 50

00:03:55.480 --> 00:03:58.700
to 75 years here and
elsewhere in the world

00:03:58.700 --> 00:04:00.880
is that those dollars
were ill spent

00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:04.630
because they didn't
incorporate people in the mix.

00:04:04.630 --> 00:04:07.780
And Lewa has really
led the charge

00:04:07.780 --> 00:04:09.520
on community conservation.

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:12.650
We started a surrogate group
called The Northern Rangelands

00:04:12.650 --> 00:04:15.100
Trust in 2004.

00:04:15.100 --> 00:04:20.170
We now have 11,000 square
miles of land in conservation

00:04:20.170 --> 00:04:23.250
management, and we're
hoping to go much further.

00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:30.470
We are a 62,000-acre
conservancy, so we're a place.

00:04:30.470 --> 00:04:33.730
But we're also a much
larger organization.

00:04:33.730 --> 00:04:35.770
We're the anchor for
this massive movement

00:04:35.770 --> 00:04:36.870
in Northern Kenya.

00:04:39.410 --> 00:04:43.060
Wildlife and community
go hand in hand.

00:04:43.060 --> 00:04:46.550
These are stats on poaching.

00:04:46.550 --> 00:04:49.250
And Community
Conservation is the name

00:04:49.250 --> 00:04:51.690
of the game, Community
Center Conservation.

00:04:51.690 --> 00:04:55.600
I'm going to show a short video
of Lewa to give you the feel

00:04:55.600 --> 00:04:56.280
right now.

00:04:58.930 --> 00:05:03.340
NARRATOR: In June of 2013,
Lewa Wildlife Conservancy

00:05:03.340 --> 00:05:06.095
was inscribed as an extension of
the Mount Kenya World Heritage

00:05:06.095 --> 00:05:09.020
Site, a testament to
the years of dedication

00:05:09.020 --> 00:05:11.680
in creating this unique
catalyst and model

00:05:11.680 --> 00:05:13.255
for community-based
conservation.

00:05:17.280 --> 00:05:18.990
IAN CRAIG: Lewa has a spirit.

00:05:18.990 --> 00:05:20.890
People work here 24 hours.

00:05:20.890 --> 00:05:22.680
They go the extra mile.

00:05:22.680 --> 00:05:24.190
And it has a heart and a soul.

00:05:24.190 --> 00:05:27.765
ANNA MERZ: I think this place
has got its [INAUDIBLE].

00:05:27.765 --> 00:05:32.615
Certainly I feel it and love it.

00:05:32.615 --> 00:05:35.400
NARRATOR: The success of the
Lewa Wildlife Conservancy

00:05:35.400 --> 00:05:36.750
is unquestionable.

00:05:36.750 --> 00:05:38.830
You only have to look at
the thriving populations

00:05:38.830 --> 00:05:41.460
of wildlife, particularly of
two notable highly endangered

00:05:41.460 --> 00:05:44.676
species, and the harmony with
the surrounding communities

00:05:44.676 --> 00:05:46.050
to know that this
is a model that

00:05:46.050 --> 00:05:48.830
works-- a catalyst
for conservation

00:05:48.830 --> 00:05:52.410
across this region of northern
Kenya and potentially way,

00:05:52.410 --> 00:05:53.702
way beyond.

00:05:53.702 --> 00:05:56.160
JOHN KINOTI: People who didn't
have water, they have water.

00:05:56.160 --> 00:05:57.740
Women who didn't
have businesses have

00:05:57.740 --> 00:06:00.090
businesses because we've
been able to involve them.

00:06:00.090 --> 00:06:02.140
It becomes like my
gasoline to move on.

00:06:02.140 --> 00:06:03.320
I can actually carry on.

00:06:43.496 --> 00:06:45.640
NARRATOR: In East Africa,
where wildlife numbers

00:06:45.640 --> 00:06:47.420
have been declining
for many years,

00:06:47.420 --> 00:06:49.586
now here is an established
and proven model

00:06:49.586 --> 00:06:50.835
which is reversing this trend.

00:06:54.970 --> 00:06:57.920
MIKE WATSON: Lewa really is the
story about one amazing woman,

00:06:57.920 --> 00:07:03.620
Anna Merz, and an
endangered species,

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:06.580
and the vision of
one man, Ian Craig.

00:07:06.580 --> 00:07:10.620
NARRATOR: In 1970, there were
20,000 black rhinos in Kenya.

00:07:10.620 --> 00:07:13.690
Through poaching, this
figure had plummeted by 98%

00:07:13.690 --> 00:07:18.010
to only 280 individuals
in just 12 years.

00:07:18.010 --> 00:07:20.110
Kenya is an exception
within East Africa

00:07:20.110 --> 00:07:22.550
in its acceptance of
private-sector partnerships

00:07:22.550 --> 00:07:24.090
and conservation.

00:07:24.090 --> 00:07:25.790
With this freedom,
Lewa has spawned

00:07:25.790 --> 00:07:28.260
a new concept in
conservation-- that

00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:31.660
of a private, public, and
community-based partnership.

00:07:31.660 --> 00:07:33.980
Of the over 600
black rhino in Kenya,

00:07:33.980 --> 00:07:36.180
a figure currently
rising at around 8%

00:07:36.180 --> 00:07:40.190
annually, 45% have found them
private sanctuaries very much

00:07:40.190 --> 00:07:42.444
modeled on Lewa.

00:07:42.444 --> 00:07:44.560
A large part of the
success is thanks

00:07:44.560 --> 00:07:47.880
to the extensive security
setup on the conservancy.

00:07:47.880 --> 00:07:50.100
MIKE WATSON: In the Lewa
Security Department,

00:07:50.100 --> 00:07:54.890
we have well over 150 people, 30
armed Kenya police reservists.

00:07:57.840 --> 00:08:01.030
They are armed by
government, and they

00:08:01.030 --> 00:08:03.560
are employed and managed by us.

00:08:09.800 --> 00:08:11.900
NARRATOR: Lewa has also
been leading the way

00:08:11.900 --> 00:08:14.680
in developing methods of
moving large numbers, sometimes

00:08:14.680 --> 00:08:17.340
hundreds of animals from
one location to another,

00:08:17.340 --> 00:08:19.710
working regularly with the
government-run Kenya Wildlife

00:08:19.710 --> 00:08:22.100
Service in joint operations.

00:08:22.100 --> 00:08:24.020
With this expertise
and the reservoir

00:08:24.020 --> 00:08:26.330
of wildlife within
Lewa, the Conservancy

00:08:26.330 --> 00:08:29.400
has huge potential to act as
a supply and source of animals

00:08:29.400 --> 00:08:30.735
for new community conservancies.

00:08:37.080 --> 00:08:38.799
The Kenya Wildlife
Service provide

00:08:38.799 --> 00:08:41.150
Lewa with a highly-skilled vet.

00:08:41.150 --> 00:08:43.190
His salary is
covered by Lewa, who

00:08:43.190 --> 00:08:47.540
also provide logistical
support and assistance.

00:08:47.540 --> 00:08:50.040
This enables him to
spread his expertise,

00:08:50.040 --> 00:08:52.080
providing timely and
effective wildlife

00:08:52.080 --> 00:08:54.450
veterinary intervention
right across the region.

00:08:59.980 --> 00:09:01.650
It is this kind of
cooperation that

00:09:01.650 --> 00:09:04.340
builds on the close alliance
and symbiotic relationship

00:09:04.340 --> 00:09:06.517
between Lewa and the
people who reside just

00:09:06.517 --> 00:09:08.100
beyond the borders
of the conservancy.

00:09:15.580 --> 00:09:18.230
Lewa's vision extends
well beyond the horizon,

00:09:18.230 --> 00:09:20.720
recognizing that the
welfare of local communities

00:09:20.720 --> 00:09:23.250
is integral to the welfare
of the ecosystems on which

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:25.120
so much depends.

00:09:25.120 --> 00:09:26.670
EDWARD NDERITU:
Through health care,

00:09:26.670 --> 00:09:29.770
through education, through
employment and security

00:09:29.770 --> 00:09:33.950
to the people who live just the
other side of the fence line.

00:09:33.950 --> 00:09:38.300
These communities act as
a first line of defense.

00:09:38.300 --> 00:09:41.030
And we will receive
information from them

00:09:41.030 --> 00:09:44.160
long before any poacher
or potential poacher

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:45.810
get foot into Lewa.

00:09:45.810 --> 00:09:48.060
JOHN KINOTI: The Lewa
Community Government Program

00:09:48.060 --> 00:09:51.730
entails dealing with the
communities around us in Lewa.

00:09:51.730 --> 00:09:53.405
We are trying to
positively influence

00:09:53.405 --> 00:09:56.050
the community towards
wildlife conservation,

00:09:56.050 --> 00:09:58.610
because we believe the
success of conservation work

00:09:58.610 --> 00:10:01.500
can only be possible if the
communities can believe in it.

00:10:01.500 --> 00:10:03.600
FAITH RIUNGA: Lewa
Wildlife Conservancy now

00:10:03.600 --> 00:10:06.020
is working with 15 schools.

00:10:06.020 --> 00:10:07.740
All these schools are
government schools.

00:10:07.740 --> 00:10:10.200
The Lewa [INAUDIBLE]
Education Program

00:10:10.200 --> 00:10:13.480
is going to be governed
by stakeholders.

00:10:13.480 --> 00:10:15.590
We will include the government.

00:10:15.590 --> 00:10:17.020
We will include KWS.

00:10:17.020 --> 00:10:20.670
We will include Lewa and
NRT, and also representatives

00:10:20.670 --> 00:10:23.840
from the community so that
the approach is holistic

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:25.770
and the needs are coming
from the community.

00:10:25.770 --> 00:10:27.270
We are happy that
this is happening,

00:10:27.270 --> 00:10:29.680
because out of this
successful program

00:10:29.680 --> 00:10:32.390
we have had here, then we shall
be able to do it elsewhere

00:10:32.390 --> 00:10:35.246
where it is needed.

00:10:35.246 --> 00:10:37.830
NARRATOR: Lewa has become
a catalyst for conservation

00:10:37.830 --> 00:10:40.260
in the region, and the
model many conservancies

00:10:40.260 --> 00:10:43.520
strive to emulate-- a model
for monitoring and protecting

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:47.970
endangered species and managing
habitat to maximize diversity.

00:10:47.970 --> 00:10:49.560
It has become a
model for ensuring

00:10:49.560 --> 00:10:52.250
that conservation benefits
local communities,

00:10:52.250 --> 00:10:54.970
a model for sustainable
conservation and research,

00:10:54.970 --> 00:10:57.990
and a model through investment
in self-generating revenue

00:10:57.990 --> 00:11:00.880
streams for securing that
conservation and perpetuity.

00:11:22.464 --> 00:11:24.340
IAN CRAIG: We've
got a foundation

00:11:24.340 --> 00:11:28.275
to move proactive,
community-based conversation

00:11:28.275 --> 00:11:31.365
across a massive landscape
of Northern Kenya.

00:11:31.365 --> 00:11:33.504
And it wouldn't without Lewa.

00:12:04.830 --> 00:12:07.860
GINGER THOMPSON: The video gives
you the sense of the place that

00:12:07.860 --> 00:12:10.510
some of you here have visited,
but most of you probably

00:12:10.510 --> 00:12:12.150
haven't.

00:12:12.150 --> 00:12:18.100
It's a small piece of land
in this vast landscape.

00:12:18.100 --> 00:12:21.820
And so much potential.

00:12:21.820 --> 00:12:24.320
We're the gateway to
this northern area,

00:12:24.320 --> 00:12:28.110
and we're also the engine room
for the actual conservation

00:12:28.110 --> 00:12:30.620
work, for the community
development work,

00:12:30.620 --> 00:12:33.340
for building buildings
that need building,

00:12:33.340 --> 00:12:35.500
for fencing where
there's fencing needed

00:12:35.500 --> 00:12:40.150
for all sorts of
road building, lots

00:12:40.150 --> 00:12:43.240
and lots of different things
that Lewa actually provides

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:49.820
the manpower, the skill set, the
talent for in Northern Kenya.

00:12:49.820 --> 00:12:56.290
I'm going to stop and let
you know that we have a goal

00:12:56.290 --> 00:13:00.780
to take 11,000 square
miles-- about the size

00:13:00.780 --> 00:13:03.600
of Massachusetts--
and grow it to 35,000

00:13:03.600 --> 00:13:08.580
square miles of open
range land for wildlife

00:13:08.580 --> 00:13:11.480
and for the pastoralist
people who live with it.

00:13:11.480 --> 00:13:14.560
And that's a great, big,
huge, enormous goal, but one

00:13:14.560 --> 00:13:16.320
that we actually
see in our sights.

00:13:16.320 --> 00:13:18.830
We see it happening
in the next 10 years.

00:13:18.830 --> 00:13:23.760
And that 35,000 square
miles, roughly the size

00:13:23.760 --> 00:13:24.900
of the state of Indiana.

00:13:24.900 --> 00:13:28.430
So it's a pretty big area.

00:13:28.430 --> 00:13:32.250
With the right help and with
all of you, we can get there.

00:13:32.250 --> 00:13:35.800
I'm just going to say one or
two words about these guys.

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:40.150
Chege has earned his stripes
as our conservation head.

00:13:40.150 --> 00:13:46.770
He was rolled over or rolled
on upon by a 1.5-ton rhino.

00:13:46.770 --> 00:13:49.600
So we all come by our
stripes in different ways,

00:13:49.600 --> 00:13:52.110
but he has a pretty unique one.

00:13:52.110 --> 00:13:54.760
And John has really
been involved

00:13:54.760 --> 00:13:56.570
in a lot of the community
development work

00:13:56.570 --> 00:14:00.770
on Lewa-- bringing solar to
schools, to health clinics.

00:14:00.770 --> 00:14:06.020
He's really single handedly
moved us into a new energy era.

00:14:06.020 --> 00:14:09.240
And granted, it may be a
first step for all of you,

00:14:09.240 --> 00:14:13.150
but it was a huge step for
this area of Northern Kenya.

00:14:13.150 --> 00:14:16.020
So we're going to
let them carry on.

00:14:16.020 --> 00:14:17.670
Thank you.

00:14:17.670 --> 00:14:20.630
And by the way, I want say
thank you to Katherine, too,

00:14:20.630 --> 00:14:22.510
for organizing us here.

00:14:22.510 --> 00:14:24.290
She is also a member
of our board now,

00:14:24.290 --> 00:14:25.884
and we're so
delighted to have her.

00:14:25.884 --> 00:14:27.050
And thank you to all of you.

00:14:32.450 --> 00:14:34.720
JOHN BATTELLE: I get to
talk about why it matters.

00:14:34.720 --> 00:14:35.820
Why should we care?

00:14:35.820 --> 00:14:39.395
Because I come to the
same place you guys do.

00:14:39.395 --> 00:14:40.270
This is our backyard.

00:14:40.270 --> 00:14:42.580
It's halfway around
the world, and we're

00:14:42.580 --> 00:14:44.160
going, why does it matter.

00:14:44.160 --> 00:14:45.780
Why do I care what
happens over there?

00:14:45.780 --> 00:14:47.170
And there's a couple
components that

00:14:47.170 --> 00:14:48.336
are really, really critical.

00:14:48.336 --> 00:14:50.690
The fact that you're sitting
here is a first step.

00:14:50.690 --> 00:14:53.940
But on a broad, global
scale, this really

00:14:53.940 --> 00:14:55.370
comes down to
challenges that are

00:14:55.370 --> 00:14:57.510
going to happen with
biodiversity and challenges

00:14:57.510 --> 00:14:58.760
with resources.

00:14:58.760 --> 00:15:01.230
The reality is we don't
have enough on the planet.

00:15:01.230 --> 00:15:02.930
And we need to link
the understanding

00:15:02.930 --> 00:15:06.820
behind biodiversity and wildlife
to the benefit of all of us.

00:15:06.820 --> 00:15:09.580
For now, the easiest one
that we can talk about

00:15:09.580 --> 00:15:11.860
is the reality around terrorism.

00:15:11.860 --> 00:15:14.810
If we're not defending
against poaching,

00:15:14.810 --> 00:15:16.480
if we're not out
there protecting

00:15:16.480 --> 00:15:20.220
wildlife and diversity
biodiversity, the activity

00:15:20.220 --> 00:15:23.000
and the civil unrest that occurs
from that affects all of us

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.390
here no matter where it's
happening around the world.

00:15:25.390 --> 00:15:27.610
We're talking about
North Kenya, bordered

00:15:27.610 --> 00:15:30.137
by Somali and Ethiopia,
and the reality

00:15:30.137 --> 00:15:32.220
is that it's a front line
of where we can actually

00:15:32.220 --> 00:15:33.490
make a difference.

00:15:33.490 --> 00:15:36.380
The beauty is that the
people in Kenya, specifically

00:15:36.380 --> 00:15:38.317
North Kenya, would
want nothing more

00:15:38.317 --> 00:15:40.650
than to be able to live the
way that they currently live

00:15:40.650 --> 00:15:41.850
and have a better life.

00:15:41.850 --> 00:15:44.840
And we have the tools, or
the beginning of the tools,

00:15:44.840 --> 00:15:45.770
to make that impact.

00:15:45.770 --> 00:15:47.920
And you guys can be
a huge part of that.

00:15:47.920 --> 00:15:50.610
So that's why we should care.

00:15:50.610 --> 00:15:53.250
The reality is that
premature extinction

00:15:53.250 --> 00:15:54.410
is going on around us.

00:15:54.410 --> 00:15:57.380
The baseline that has been
measured way back when,

00:15:57.380 --> 00:15:59.200
they measured what
the plant normally

00:15:59.200 --> 00:16:00.960
would handle in
terms of extinction.

00:16:00.960 --> 00:16:04.420
In 2005, we were-- I'm going
to flip my slide here--

00:16:04.420 --> 00:16:08.654
we were 1,000 times the level
of natural premature extinction.

00:16:08.654 --> 00:16:10.237
By the end of the
century, they expect

00:16:10.237 --> 00:16:13.450
it to be 10,000
times that level.

00:16:13.450 --> 00:16:15.370
And the fact is that
when the planet is

00:16:15.370 --> 00:16:17.990
going through this exercise of
trying to adjust to what humans

00:16:17.990 --> 00:16:21.290
are doing, it can't keep up.

00:16:21.290 --> 00:16:24.440
50% of the population
on this planet

00:16:24.440 --> 00:16:26.720
get its livelihood from
biodiversity and natural

00:16:26.720 --> 00:16:27.790
resources.

00:16:27.790 --> 00:16:29.640
And if those aren't
there, their livelihoods

00:16:29.640 --> 00:16:31.770
go away-- their
ability to eat, ability

00:16:31.770 --> 00:16:33.980
to find jobs,
ability to survive.

00:16:33.980 --> 00:16:35.860
And that turns back
into the first slide,

00:16:35.860 --> 00:16:38.680
which is about this challenge
of why we should care.

00:16:38.680 --> 00:16:40.380
We look at premature
extinction, which

00:16:40.380 --> 00:16:43.500
is happening at a much more
rapid rate, caused by us.

00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:45.670
We have the loss
of biodiversity,

00:16:45.670 --> 00:16:49.050
the loss of livelihood,
food, water resources.

00:16:49.050 --> 00:16:51.690
And in the end, it affects
everyone on this planet.

00:16:51.690 --> 00:16:54.110
So we need to make this jump
to understanding this bigger

00:16:54.110 --> 00:16:54.610
picture.

00:16:54.610 --> 00:16:56.276
And I know you guys
are capable of that.

00:16:56.276 --> 00:16:57.320
You guys do it every day.

00:16:57.320 --> 00:16:58.560
You're looking way out there.

00:16:58.560 --> 00:17:00.330
What we want to talk
to you today about

00:17:00.330 --> 00:17:02.964
is how we take that
vision and your skills

00:17:02.964 --> 00:17:04.380
and figure out how
we can actually

00:17:04.380 --> 00:17:07.910
map better picture specifically
right now in North Kenya.

00:17:07.910 --> 00:17:08.410
Chege.

00:17:08.410 --> 00:17:11.970
GEOFFERY CHEGE:
Thank you very much.

00:17:11.970 --> 00:17:16.550
And thank you, Ginger, for such
positive compliments regarding

00:17:16.550 --> 00:17:19.410
being rolled over by a rhino.

00:17:19.410 --> 00:17:21.130
It doesn't happen every day.

00:17:21.130 --> 00:17:25.300
But the moment as it comes to
Lewa, take it as a challenge

00:17:25.300 --> 00:17:26.750
and you move on.

00:17:26.750 --> 00:17:29.740
And I thank god that I'm
standing right in front of you

00:17:29.740 --> 00:17:32.450
today to talk about
my experience.

00:17:32.450 --> 00:17:38.260
But that aside, we
believe that technology

00:17:38.260 --> 00:17:41.625
has got a significant role
to support conservation,

00:17:41.625 --> 00:17:44.700
to support protection,
and to support

00:17:44.700 --> 00:17:48.450
the security of wildlife
and people in Kenya

00:17:48.450 --> 00:17:51.100
and all over the world.

00:17:51.100 --> 00:17:54.030
And as we try to
understand nature,

00:17:54.030 --> 00:17:56.260
as we try to make the
linkage between the wildlife

00:17:56.260 --> 00:17:58.940
and community development,
we have quite a number

00:17:58.940 --> 00:18:02.710
of technological advancements
that we have implemented

00:18:02.710 --> 00:18:05.940
on the ground in an
attempt to secure

00:18:05.940 --> 00:18:10.310
the land both for
wildlife and for people.

00:18:10.310 --> 00:18:13.170
Part of the technology
that we're talking about

00:18:13.170 --> 00:18:18.950
include fixing of
GPS tracking devices

00:18:18.950 --> 00:18:21.200
on wildlife, on
elephants, on rhinos,

00:18:21.200 --> 00:18:25.130
so that we know exactly where
they are on a real-time basis.

00:18:25.130 --> 00:18:29.390
We are more into
fixing of camera traps.

00:18:29.390 --> 00:18:34.120
Ginger mentioned about Lewa been
small, being completely fenced,

00:18:34.120 --> 00:18:37.270
but we have quite a number
of gaps that allow wildlife

00:18:37.270 --> 00:18:39.412
to come in and go out.

00:18:39.412 --> 00:18:41.370
So we have fixed quite
a number camera traps so

00:18:41.370 --> 00:18:43.950
that we can understand the
dynamics of the movement one

00:18:43.950 --> 00:18:47.590
wildlife outside and
then when they come back.

00:18:47.590 --> 00:18:51.610
We are very much into digital
radio communication, which

00:18:51.610 --> 00:18:55.670
is very important in
this era of poaching,

00:18:55.670 --> 00:18:59.060
in this era of terrorism, in
this era of insecurity issues

00:18:59.060 --> 00:19:00.991
that John has just alluded to.

00:19:00.991 --> 00:19:03.240
Digital communication that
we are using at the moment,

00:19:03.240 --> 00:19:05.640
they are secure,
they are encrypted,

00:19:05.640 --> 00:19:07.580
and there is no
way that anyone is

00:19:07.580 --> 00:19:11.740
going to hack into them unless
you've been given access to it.

00:19:11.740 --> 00:19:16.600
We are starting to get much more
into ID-based identification,

00:19:16.600 --> 00:19:19.350
individual wildlife
identification software,

00:19:19.350 --> 00:19:23.460
so that we can track individual
animals on a daily basis,

00:19:23.460 --> 00:19:25.270
on a monthly basis,
annual basis,

00:19:25.270 --> 00:19:29.240
and then we can recreate their
life history tables, their life

00:19:29.240 --> 00:19:33.200
history strategies as we
move forward, we move on.

00:19:33.200 --> 00:19:35.890
All of these are an
attempt to secure

00:19:35.890 --> 00:19:40.470
space for wildlife
and also people.

00:19:40.470 --> 00:19:43.480
Everything that we are doing,
we are not doing on our own.

00:19:43.480 --> 00:19:47.130
We are unto partnerships
with very many people.

00:19:47.130 --> 00:19:49.170
We believe that
scale is critical,

00:19:49.170 --> 00:19:51.690
and that's why we have
partnered with other people

00:19:51.690 --> 00:19:55.720
in the region, including
a group like you,

00:19:55.720 --> 00:19:57.430
including people
like you, because we

00:19:57.430 --> 00:19:59.970
believe in tapping the
right kind of expertise.

00:19:59.970 --> 00:20:03.070
And that's one of the
reasons why we are here.

00:20:03.070 --> 00:20:05.900
We are into collaboration
and partnership

00:20:05.900 --> 00:20:08.620
with Save The Elephants,
of which some of you

00:20:08.620 --> 00:20:11.850
may be aware about that
particular organization.

00:20:11.850 --> 00:20:14.830
We're in partnership with the
Zoological Society of London.

00:20:14.830 --> 00:20:17.530
We are in partnership with
the Kenya Wildlife Studies,

00:20:17.530 --> 00:20:20.010
with the Custodians of Wildlife.

00:20:20.010 --> 00:20:23.030
In Kenya, we are in
partnership with Sarfaricom,

00:20:23.030 --> 00:20:26.510
who are the biggest
mobile telephony provider

00:20:26.510 --> 00:20:30.360
in the country, WildlifeDirect,
and several zoos

00:20:30.360 --> 00:20:33.345
and many other conservation
organizations in all

00:20:33.345 --> 00:20:35.036
over the world.

00:20:35.036 --> 00:20:36.620
JOHN BATTELLE:
What's coming next?

00:20:36.620 --> 00:20:38.810
This is actually a
pretty easy step for us.

00:20:38.810 --> 00:20:42.757
If you look at what
we've done in the past,

00:20:42.757 --> 00:20:44.840
a few years ago, if we
could get a solar panel up,

00:20:44.840 --> 00:20:46.340
we were really kicking butt.

00:20:46.340 --> 00:20:48.860
But the reality is
that the ability

00:20:48.860 --> 00:20:52.760
to do that is pretty simple
now in terms of solar, wind,

00:20:52.760 --> 00:20:55.132
LED lighting, all that
kind of technology.

00:20:55.132 --> 00:20:56.840
There actually is
infrastructure in place

00:20:56.840 --> 00:21:00.310
that's usable and functions
pretty well within East Africa,

00:21:00.310 --> 00:21:01.649
specifically in Kenya.

00:21:01.649 --> 00:21:03.940
So those resources are things
that we don't necessarily

00:21:03.940 --> 00:21:05.040
focus on.

00:21:05.040 --> 00:21:07.160
Cellular technology,
a huge shift for us

00:21:07.160 --> 00:21:09.415
which really affects you
guys from our standpoint

00:21:09.415 --> 00:21:11.160
and why we can use
you even more today

00:21:11.160 --> 00:21:13.050
than we could five years ago.

00:21:13.050 --> 00:21:14.430
Originally, and
even today, we're

00:21:14.430 --> 00:21:16.630
really still in the voice
communication world.

00:21:16.630 --> 00:21:18.570
We're just moving
into the data world.

00:21:18.570 --> 00:21:20.180
But the ability from
a cellular tower

00:21:20.180 --> 00:21:21.660
perspective to
get communications

00:21:21.660 --> 00:21:24.140
over large regions,
that's happening.

00:21:24.140 --> 00:21:26.450
So we're now looking at
first-generation apps,

00:21:26.450 --> 00:21:30.080
first-generation baking
tools, those kind of things.

00:21:30.080 --> 00:21:31.770
And those are where
we are at today.

00:21:31.770 --> 00:21:33.420
We're looking at
that high-level,

00:21:33.420 --> 00:21:37.020
granulizing those down into
the next generation of things.

00:21:37.020 --> 00:21:40.090
So we're leveraging
smart spatial monitoring

00:21:40.090 --> 00:21:41.260
for conservation.

00:21:41.260 --> 00:21:43.414
We're looking at things
for security like drones.

00:21:43.414 --> 00:21:44.830
Everybody is talking
about drones.

00:21:44.830 --> 00:21:46.820
We are looking at
forward-looking infrared.

00:21:46.820 --> 00:21:50.620
We're looking at better ways to
use existing technology that's

00:21:50.620 --> 00:21:52.506
cheaper and faster and so forth.

00:21:52.506 --> 00:21:54.130
But that's not the
leap we need to make

00:21:54.130 --> 00:21:59.120
if we're going to take over
and try to develop 35,000

00:21:59.120 --> 00:22:01.420
square miles of land
for conservation.

00:22:01.420 --> 00:22:02.790
We have to really take a leap.

00:22:02.790 --> 00:22:05.310
But today we're in this
phase of really starting

00:22:05.310 --> 00:22:08.410
to bring technology to bear
on a lot of the core things

00:22:08.410 --> 00:22:09.870
that we're doing today.

00:22:09.870 --> 00:22:13.580
GEOFFERY CHEGE: I think I
would like to dive into some

00:22:13.580 --> 00:22:15.750
of the challenges
that we're facing

00:22:15.750 --> 00:22:19.500
in Kenya at the moment and
indeed the entire North Kenya

00:22:19.500 --> 00:22:20.680
landscape.

00:22:20.680 --> 00:22:22.630
And one of the most
critical points

00:22:22.630 --> 00:22:25.380
is the issue about insecurity.

00:22:25.380 --> 00:22:28.860
My colleague Ginger
alluded about poaching.

00:22:28.860 --> 00:22:32.280
We need to secure the landscape
for the benefit of wildlife

00:22:32.280 --> 00:22:33.600
and people.

00:22:33.600 --> 00:22:37.000
Without security, then
there's nothing far.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:39.270
We will not move far.

00:22:39.270 --> 00:22:42.290
We need to reduce the
international demand

00:22:42.290 --> 00:22:45.540
for wildlife products.

00:22:45.540 --> 00:22:48.240
That is something that
we have got to do.

00:22:48.240 --> 00:22:50.380
It is all linked to terrorism.

00:22:50.380 --> 00:22:51.235
It is affecting us.

00:22:51.235 --> 00:22:52.110
It is a global issue.

00:22:52.110 --> 00:22:54.950
And we've got to
fight it as a team.

00:22:54.950 --> 00:22:58.650
We need to ensure that we engage
the right kind of community

00:22:58.650 --> 00:22:59.440
partnership.

00:22:59.440 --> 00:23:02.050
We need to bring on
board the communities

00:23:02.050 --> 00:23:03.740
so that we can secure
their livelihood,

00:23:03.740 --> 00:23:06.360
we can secure their health
care, we can secure their water

00:23:06.360 --> 00:23:09.010
needs, we can secure
their educational needs,

00:23:09.010 --> 00:23:10.260
and everything.

00:23:10.260 --> 00:23:11.645
The other major
challenge that we

00:23:11.645 --> 00:23:15.770
are facing in the country at the
moment is population explosion.

00:23:15.770 --> 00:23:17.600
In 2012, the
population of Kenya was

00:23:17.600 --> 00:23:20.310
approximated to be
about 44 million.

00:23:20.310 --> 00:23:22.050
By 2050, it is
projected that it is

00:23:22.050 --> 00:23:24.600
going to be about 94 million.

00:23:24.600 --> 00:23:27.800
And that is a
significant growth.

00:23:27.800 --> 00:23:30.420
What does it bring on board?

00:23:30.420 --> 00:23:33.770
One is that there is going
to be massive pressure

00:23:33.770 --> 00:23:35.030
on the resources.

00:23:35.030 --> 00:23:37.210
That is going to lead
to habitat degradation.

00:23:37.210 --> 00:23:39.140
It is going to lead
to habitat loss.

00:23:39.140 --> 00:23:42.100
It is going to lead to
isolation of landscapes

00:23:42.100 --> 00:23:44.000
that were initially
interconnected

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:46.010
for the benefit of wildlife.

00:23:46.010 --> 00:23:50.524
I'm not forgetting the increment
in the human wildlife conflict.

00:23:50.524 --> 00:23:52.690
The other challenge that
we are facing at the moment

00:23:52.690 --> 00:23:58.320
is that it's only about 40%
of the country's wildlife

00:23:58.320 --> 00:24:00.637
that is within the
formally protected areas.

00:24:00.637 --> 00:24:02.470
It could be government,
it could be private,

00:24:02.470 --> 00:24:05.790
it could be community.

00:24:05.790 --> 00:24:11.450
But 60% of Kenya's
wildlife lives

00:24:11.450 --> 00:24:14.020
in areas that are not
formally protected.

00:24:14.020 --> 00:24:16.860
And this is where now you've
got the greatest opportunity

00:24:16.860 --> 00:24:20.110
in terms of jumping in and
ensuring that that place is

00:24:20.110 --> 00:24:25.640
secure for the benefit of
not just wildlife but people.

00:24:25.640 --> 00:24:28.070
My colleague Ginger
alluded about Lewa

00:24:28.070 --> 00:24:31.860
being a kind of place in scale.

00:24:31.860 --> 00:24:33.860
I just want to give you
a context of what you're

00:24:33.860 --> 00:24:37.650
talking about in relation to
the entire of Northern Kenya.

00:24:37.650 --> 00:24:39.620
Lewa is just this tiny
piece that is over here,

00:24:39.620 --> 00:24:42.260
62,000 acres of land.

00:24:42.260 --> 00:24:44.240
And what you're
seeing farther north

00:24:44.240 --> 00:24:49.120
in terms of all of these
yellows is a significant matrix

00:24:49.120 --> 00:24:50.780
of community
conservation areas that

00:24:50.780 --> 00:24:55.450
have established under the
umbrella of the Northern

00:24:55.450 --> 00:24:57.800
Rangelands Trust.

00:24:57.800 --> 00:25:03.290
On our south, we've got the
government-owned North Kenya

00:25:03.290 --> 00:25:05.880
forest and national park.

00:25:05.880 --> 00:25:10.080
So the current area that has
been protected at the moment

00:25:10.080 --> 00:25:13.170
is just about
11,000 square miles.

00:25:13.170 --> 00:25:15.890
And you would like to increase
that one to scale it up

00:25:15.890 --> 00:25:18.590
about 5,000 square miles.

00:25:18.590 --> 00:25:21.030
We've got great
opportunities that I've just

00:25:21.030 --> 00:25:23.510
presented along the
way, and especially

00:25:23.510 --> 00:25:25.360
in the last few years.

00:25:25.360 --> 00:25:29.810
One of them is about
the new wildlife act.

00:25:29.810 --> 00:25:35.360
Our president just signed
the new wildlife act in 2013.

00:25:35.360 --> 00:25:39.050
Part of that act is it is
galvanizing conservation

00:25:39.050 --> 00:25:41.670
as an alternative
for more land use.

00:25:41.670 --> 00:25:44.580
It is galvanizing the
establishment of conservancies

00:25:44.580 --> 00:25:46.960
as an alternative for land use.

00:25:46.960 --> 00:25:48.660
It could be community.

00:25:48.660 --> 00:25:51.350
It could be private owned.

00:25:51.350 --> 00:25:56.880
Last year, we got in to the new
constitution in the country.

00:25:56.880 --> 00:25:59.710
It is devolving
functions that initially

00:25:59.710 --> 00:26:02.800
used to be vested in
the state government.

00:26:02.800 --> 00:26:04.934
So things to do with
management of some

00:26:04.934 --> 00:26:06.350
of the natural
resources have been

00:26:06.350 --> 00:26:07.950
invested in the
county government

00:26:07.950 --> 00:26:09.490
or the regional government.

00:26:09.490 --> 00:26:11.460
And they're making
significant contributions

00:26:11.460 --> 00:26:14.280
so that they can secure those
landscapes and wildlife so

00:26:14.280 --> 00:26:17.700
that they can benefit
their particular region.

00:26:17.700 --> 00:26:23.740
And number three is that all
of these landscapes, the yellow

00:26:23.740 --> 00:26:26.160
polygons over here,
they are all managed

00:26:26.160 --> 00:26:28.470
under the umbrella of
a Northern Rangelands

00:26:28.470 --> 00:26:31.050
Trust, which is formed in 2004.

00:26:31.050 --> 00:26:33.480
It was born out of Lewa.

00:26:33.480 --> 00:26:35.420
So opportunities are there.

00:26:35.420 --> 00:26:36.770
[INAUDIBLE] is growing.

00:26:36.770 --> 00:26:39.450
And we need to
partner with everyone

00:26:39.450 --> 00:26:44.470
and bring everyone on board so
that we can move and scale up.

00:26:44.470 --> 00:26:46.960
GINGER THOMPSON: I think
it's important to note

00:26:46.960 --> 00:26:50.800
that those yellow areas
