00:27:20.790 --> 00:27:23.020
In working with
pastoral communities,

00:27:23.020 --> 00:27:25.750
we looked at how do we protect
wildlife and give you income

00:27:25.750 --> 00:27:28.549
without you breaking apart
the potential for wildlife.

00:27:28.549 --> 00:27:31.090
And this is where a lot of these
have been developing out of.

00:27:31.090 --> 00:27:32.980
This is way before the act.

00:27:32.980 --> 00:27:35.960
And now the act gives us
leverage to do it even grander

00:27:35.960 --> 00:27:38.046
as well as give legitimacy
to the exercises

00:27:38.046 --> 00:27:39.920
that we're trying to
accomplish to the north.

00:27:39.920 --> 00:27:42.170
GEOFFERY CHEGE: Thank you
very much, John and Ginger.

00:27:42.170 --> 00:27:46.190
I think it's very critical,
because there are tools-- where

00:27:46.190 --> 00:27:48.240
it was being crafted, it
was very consultative.

00:27:48.240 --> 00:27:54.370
So what is happening in Northern
Kenya informed the new act.

00:27:54.370 --> 00:28:00.370
In terms of why we need to
forecast on Kenya's vast lands,

00:28:00.370 --> 00:28:05.500
Kenya's wilderness, one critical
point is that Kenya is vast.

00:28:05.500 --> 00:28:10.540
It has got some very vast, open
landscapes, which presents us

00:28:10.540 --> 00:28:13.280
with some perfect
opportunity in terms

00:28:13.280 --> 00:28:16.010
of conserving the
wildlife that is there

00:28:16.010 --> 00:28:19.380
and ensuring the livelihoods
of the people who

00:28:19.380 --> 00:28:22.950
live amidst to the wildlife
that is integrated within.

00:28:22.950 --> 00:28:24.390
Why is that possible?

00:28:24.390 --> 00:28:27.720
Because Kenya has got some
of these few landscapes

00:28:27.720 --> 00:28:33.630
where wildlife and people
do live side to side.

00:28:33.630 --> 00:28:37.630
Going back to the 1960s the
1970s, what used to happen

00:28:37.630 --> 00:28:41.460
is that we used to have
abundant wildlife densities.

00:28:41.460 --> 00:28:43.480
These used to be a
lot in Northern Kenya.

00:28:43.480 --> 00:28:45.720
But in the late
1970s, they were all

00:28:45.720 --> 00:28:48.130
decimated because of
quite a number of factors,

00:28:48.130 --> 00:28:50.320
of which poaching was
one of them to supply

00:28:50.320 --> 00:28:52.870
the legal markets.

00:28:52.870 --> 00:28:54.550
We had bush meat poaching.

00:28:54.550 --> 00:28:59.080
We had incremented a
population of people.

00:28:59.080 --> 00:29:02.600
And all that has been
bringing significant pressure

00:29:02.600 --> 00:29:04.280
on the resources.

00:29:04.280 --> 00:29:08.730
But now with an evolved
government, with a new wildlife

00:29:08.730 --> 00:29:12.160
act, with Lewa being on board,
with all the other partners who

00:29:12.160 --> 00:29:15.640
are on board, we've got
a perfect opportunity

00:29:15.640 --> 00:29:20.330
of recreating buck
what used to be there.

00:29:20.330 --> 00:29:25.000
So our vision as of now is
that it is very possible

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:29.464
to use technology so that
we can secure the landscapes

00:29:29.464 --> 00:29:30.630
for the benefit of wildlife.

00:29:30.630 --> 00:29:33.300
And we make that particular
wildlife continue

00:29:33.300 --> 00:29:35.455
being abundant and
actually flourish.

00:29:37.651 --> 00:29:39.400
JOHN BATTELLE: You can
leave that slide up

00:29:39.400 --> 00:29:40.660
for a second, Ginger.

00:29:40.660 --> 00:29:44.130
Because there's two points
that I want to say about that.

00:29:44.130 --> 00:29:46.330
What we're talking
about is how do

00:29:46.330 --> 00:29:50.900
we empower communities
that are there

00:29:50.900 --> 00:29:53.940
to be able to survive the way
that they choose to survive

00:29:53.940 --> 00:29:55.340
within their own communities.

00:29:55.340 --> 00:29:57.340
And the way to do
that is holistically.

00:29:57.340 --> 00:30:00.860
It's a way to
integrate how they live

00:30:00.860 --> 00:30:02.690
with advancements
in technologies

00:30:02.690 --> 00:30:06.270
and bettering their ability to
drive income from how they live

00:30:06.270 --> 00:30:08.050
amongst the land and
amongst the wildlife.

00:30:08.050 --> 00:30:10.614
How do we mitigate
challenges with wildlife

00:30:10.614 --> 00:30:12.780
so that they need the
wildlife and want the wildlife

00:30:12.780 --> 00:30:13.381
to be there?

00:30:13.381 --> 00:30:14.880
Because that also
brings them income

00:30:14.880 --> 00:30:17.454
through eco lodging and all
kinds of other components,

00:30:17.454 --> 00:30:19.620
which we'll get you some
examples of in a little bit

00:30:19.620 --> 00:30:21.036
about some of
things we're working

00:30:21.036 --> 00:30:22.800
on which can explain
a little better.

00:30:22.800 --> 00:30:25.370
But our vision
that we're looking

00:30:25.370 --> 00:30:27.930
at in the future-- you want
to move up on the slide--

00:30:27.930 --> 00:30:29.880
the vision that
we're looking at is

00:30:29.880 --> 00:30:33.050
what we're calling a
technological organism.

00:30:33.050 --> 00:30:36.950
The way that I look at that is
that it's like a human body.

00:30:36.950 --> 00:30:38.220
We have a heart.

00:30:38.220 --> 00:30:39.480
We have a liver.

00:30:39.480 --> 00:30:40.430
We have a kidney.

00:30:40.430 --> 00:30:41.100
We have lungs.

00:30:41.100 --> 00:30:43.433
We have all these things that
can function independently

00:30:43.433 --> 00:30:46.440
of each other and have
very specific tasks.

00:30:46.440 --> 00:30:48.190
But they do not
function and can't

00:30:48.190 --> 00:30:51.340
survive unless the whole is
functioning and surviving.

00:30:51.340 --> 00:30:53.660
So they need to work
together in order to do that.

00:30:53.660 --> 00:30:56.150
And this is about working
with multiple communities

00:30:56.150 --> 00:31:01.420
across a large area to create
a functioning organism that

00:31:01.420 --> 00:31:04.410
can function and work
together on multiple levels

00:31:04.410 --> 00:31:07.220
so that everyone can
succeed-- not only wildlife,

00:31:07.220 --> 00:31:08.440
but also community.

00:31:08.440 --> 00:31:09.850
And that's we're talking
about trying to create.

00:31:09.850 --> 00:31:11.490
That's a vision that we
need to come up with.

00:31:11.490 --> 00:31:12.448
GINGER THOMPSON: Sorry.

00:31:12.448 --> 00:31:17.100
We really believe it's
possible to connect people

00:31:17.100 --> 00:31:22.260
in different places so that
if I have my cattle over here

00:31:22.260 --> 00:31:24.350
and there's a pride of
lion coming through,

00:31:24.350 --> 00:31:26.380
somebody can warn me
that the lion are there

00:31:26.380 --> 00:31:30.450
and I won't put my cattle in
a nighttime boma or protected

00:31:30.450 --> 00:31:32.880
area near where the
lion are coming.

00:31:32.880 --> 00:31:35.490
I can move them a little
bit further afield

00:31:35.490 --> 00:31:38.040
and herd them to a
different location,

00:31:38.040 --> 00:31:40.480
and therefore I won't
lose my livestock

00:31:40.480 --> 00:31:43.244
when the lions come through.

00:31:43.244 --> 00:31:45.410
JOHN BATTELLE: The point
is, what we're evolving is,

00:31:45.410 --> 00:31:48.000
we need to develop a very
sophisticated management

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:54.280
platform that can be dynamic
and changing, that can handle

00:31:54.280 --> 00:31:56.120
the amount of data and
the amount of points

00:31:56.120 --> 00:31:57.786
that we would want
to be able to handle,

00:31:57.786 --> 00:31:59.860
and be able to
recognize spatially

00:31:59.860 --> 00:32:01.140
the differences between them.

00:32:01.140 --> 00:32:03.306
And I'm not talking about
smart technology everybody

00:32:03.306 --> 00:32:05.920
is talking about today, which
is really about a single focus

00:32:05.920 --> 00:32:09.220
conservation approach and
solving a specific problem

00:32:09.220 --> 00:32:12.205
spatially for rangers
in a conservancy.

00:32:12.205 --> 00:32:14.380
There's a lot of great
technology coming out.

00:32:14.380 --> 00:32:15.890
What I'm talking
about is spatially

00:32:15.890 --> 00:32:17.890
looking across
multiple communities

00:32:17.890 --> 00:32:19.770
doing different activities.

00:32:19.770 --> 00:32:21.150
One might be a farmer.

00:32:21.150 --> 00:32:23.450
One community might
be pastoralists.

00:32:23.450 --> 00:32:24.990
Another one might
be herding goats.

00:32:24.990 --> 00:32:28.190
Another one might actually be
developing some other thing.

00:32:28.190 --> 00:32:33.040
We need to be able to see across
35,000 square miles with all

00:32:33.040 --> 00:32:35.550
these different conservation
managers, with all

00:32:35.550 --> 00:32:38.500
the different elders, with
all the different conflicting

00:32:38.500 --> 00:32:41.350
issues that go on and be able to
support those organizations as

00:32:41.350 --> 00:32:42.227
though it's living.

00:32:42.227 --> 00:32:44.310
And to do that, we need a
management platform that

00:32:44.310 --> 00:32:46.460
can support that,
and we need tools

00:32:46.460 --> 00:32:48.740
that can adapt to each
individual component

00:32:48.740 --> 00:32:51.390
and work interconnectedly
together so that we

00:32:51.390 --> 00:32:54.480
can look at it on a much bigger
scale and be able to say that.

00:32:54.480 --> 00:32:56.560
We need really strong
push-pull technologies,

00:32:56.560 --> 00:32:57.810
like Ginger was talking about.

00:32:57.810 --> 00:33:00.860
We need be able to alert
particular areas that hey,

00:33:00.860 --> 00:33:03.400
there's a lion in your area,
so don't put your cattle there

00:33:03.400 --> 00:33:03.900
today.

00:33:03.900 --> 00:33:06.579
Because if a lion kills
the cattle, guess what,

00:33:06.579 --> 00:33:07.870
they're going to kill the lion.

00:33:07.870 --> 00:33:09.540
But the lion
actually brings them

00:33:09.540 --> 00:33:12.100
other income and other
biodiversity, which they need.

00:33:12.100 --> 00:33:14.540
But it's hard to
necessarily get that across.

00:33:14.540 --> 00:33:17.860
So we need to be able to
look at a much bigger scale.

00:33:17.860 --> 00:33:20.520
We need to be able to look at
one community over here who's

00:33:20.520 --> 00:33:24.200
making beads for income and
connect it to a community that

00:33:24.200 --> 00:33:28.170
could be 100 miles
away making necklaces

00:33:28.170 --> 00:33:30.650
that needs beads instead of
them buying beads from China.

00:33:30.650 --> 00:33:32.880
We need to be able to see
things completely different

00:33:32.880 --> 00:33:34.004
than we can see them today.

00:33:34.004 --> 00:33:36.490
Because today, while we're
getting more granular,

00:33:36.490 --> 00:33:38.570
we're still singularly
silo focused.

00:33:38.570 --> 00:33:41.280
Because we can't see
across those problems yet.

00:33:41.280 --> 00:33:44.750
So this is where
your ability to help

00:33:44.750 --> 00:33:48.565
us look at this in a different
can be really valuable to us.

00:33:48.565 --> 00:33:51.080
GINGER THOMPSON: We have
a whole lot of examples,

00:33:51.080 --> 00:33:53.760
but we also have a little
bit of a time crunch.

00:33:53.760 --> 00:33:56.540
So we're going to
go very quickly

00:33:56.540 --> 00:33:59.150
through a couple of examples
of work that we're doing,

00:33:59.150 --> 00:34:02.500
and you can get a sense
of how things can change.

00:34:02.500 --> 00:34:04.170
It's going to be very quick.

