So it was about
willing partners who

00:39:59.640 --> 00:40:02.020
came on board, realized
that there was a problem,

00:40:02.020 --> 00:40:04.802
and then they put their minds
together to solve the problem.

00:40:04.802 --> 00:40:07.260
GINGER THOMPSON: There's a lot
of generosity involved, too,

00:40:07.260 --> 00:40:08.490
on the landowners' part.

00:40:08.490 --> 00:40:12.150
They contribute the
land to it, farmers did.

00:40:12.150 --> 00:40:14.320
And obviously there
were individuals.

00:40:14.320 --> 00:40:16.900
In fact, there's one
lady who contributed

00:40:16.900 --> 00:40:19.750
most of the actual cash
who is right from here,

00:40:19.750 --> 00:40:23.100
from Palo Alto, and
heard about this

00:40:23.100 --> 00:40:25.800
and thought that was something
she wanted to support.

00:40:25.800 --> 00:40:27.580
So it's very local.

00:40:30.810 --> 00:40:33.180
Let's see. "Are there plans
to share these learnings

00:40:33.180 --> 00:40:35.950
and strategies with other
wildlife organizations?"

00:40:35.950 --> 00:40:37.630
It just disappeared again.

00:40:37.630 --> 00:40:38.640
Sorry.

00:40:38.640 --> 00:40:42.040
"Namely, tiger
conservancies in India."

00:40:42.040 --> 00:40:46.360
Lewa hosts groups from
all over the world on Lewa

00:40:46.360 --> 00:40:52.090
to be a demonstration site for
how you can manage wildlife

00:40:52.090 --> 00:40:58.290
in contiguous areas or in
sparsely-connected areas.

00:40:58.290 --> 00:41:02.600
So we've had people-- huge
groups from China, in fact.

00:41:02.600 --> 00:41:05.210
There is a conservancy
now in Southern China

00:41:05.210 --> 00:41:07.300
that has been modeled on Lewa.

00:41:07.300 --> 00:41:11.240
There are conservancy
groups all over Africa

00:41:11.240 --> 00:41:14.980
that come and visit and spend
two or three weeks at a time

00:41:14.980 --> 00:41:18.490
training with our
people, including Chege.

00:41:21.780 --> 00:41:23.450
We haven't done a
lot of publishing

00:41:23.450 --> 00:41:26.760
in terms of written work,
but we plan to do a lot more.

00:41:26.760 --> 00:41:29.630
Our research team was
expanded quite dramatically

00:41:29.630 --> 00:41:33.300
in the past 14 months.

00:41:33.300 --> 00:41:35.614
Chege can talk more
about that if you

00:41:35.614 --> 00:41:36.780
want to ask questions after.

00:41:36.780 --> 00:41:37.780
But absolutely.

00:41:37.780 --> 00:41:38.770
We host people.

00:41:38.770 --> 00:41:40.410
We want to share
this information.

00:41:40.410 --> 00:41:42.880
And we'll be publishing
quite a few reports

00:41:42.880 --> 00:41:45.190
in the next year or two.

00:41:45.190 --> 00:41:47.650
"What technological
hindrances exist

00:41:47.650 --> 00:41:49.570
and how can we, Google, help?"

00:41:49.570 --> 00:41:52.340
JOHN BATTELLE: That
is a great question.

00:41:52.340 --> 00:41:55.780
And the answer is
the biggest challenge

00:41:55.780 --> 00:41:59.160
we face right now
is understanding

00:41:59.160 --> 00:42:03.720
how to tackle on
such a large scale

00:42:03.720 --> 00:42:05.730
the management of
all the things we

00:42:05.730 --> 00:42:08.820
will need to be able to monitor.

00:42:08.820 --> 00:42:11.310
We're not even equipped to
understand that problem.

00:42:11.310 --> 00:42:14.760
We're not equipped to
understand all the tools

00:42:14.760 --> 00:42:17.340
that we would need to
have within those devices,

00:42:17.340 --> 00:42:19.040
within the baskets,
to be able to look

00:42:19.040 --> 00:42:22.100
at how to solve this
problem versus this problem.

00:42:22.100 --> 00:42:25.990
So I think my answer is that I
don't have a clear picture yet.

00:42:25.990 --> 00:42:27.722
I just know what I
need to be able to do,

00:42:27.722 --> 00:42:29.430
what we need to be
able to do, what we're

00:42:29.430 --> 00:42:31.367
looking at in terms
of this problem.

00:42:31.367 --> 00:42:33.450
Because this is going to
scale with or without us.

00:42:33.450 --> 00:42:36.110
But technology is going
to make it successful.

00:42:36.110 --> 00:42:37.900
It can't be
successful without it.

00:42:37.900 --> 00:42:41.210
But we need to be able to
link all of these variables

00:42:41.210 --> 00:42:43.700
and components together
through technology.

00:42:43.700 --> 00:42:45.556
And I have no clue
how to actually do it.

00:42:45.556 --> 00:42:46.930
That's what we
need you guys for.

00:42:46.930 --> 00:42:47.355
GINGER THOMPSON: Yeah.

00:42:47.355 --> 00:42:48.870
That's where we need your help.

00:42:48.870 --> 00:42:50.810
Also, energy is a
big piece of this.

00:42:50.810 --> 00:42:54.730
Because we obviously need power
to make this happen and make

00:42:54.730 --> 00:42:57.370
this a reality, and this
is a very rural area.

00:42:57.370 --> 00:42:59.690
There isn't much power up there.

00:42:59.690 --> 00:43:02.230
Some power coming in through
some projects I think you guys

00:43:02.230 --> 00:43:02.979
are involved with.

00:43:02.979 --> 00:43:06.450
But to distribute that at
a very grassroots level

00:43:06.450 --> 00:43:08.710
is really, really important.

00:43:08.710 --> 00:43:12.660
The mobile access has
actually stepped up.

00:43:12.660 --> 00:43:15.620
Safaricom is making
an inroad into really

00:43:15.620 --> 00:43:17.180
increasing mobile access.

00:43:17.180 --> 00:43:20.237
But energy is a big one.

00:43:20.237 --> 00:43:21.820
AUDIENCE: In terms
of the communities,

00:43:21.820 --> 00:43:23.444
you talked about both
building schools,

00:43:23.444 --> 00:43:26.710
bringing water, things like
that, and also creating revenue

00:43:26.710 --> 00:43:28.110
streams-- this
was in the video--

00:43:28.110 --> 00:43:30.797
so that the conservation effort
continues in the long term.

00:43:30.797 --> 00:43:33.130
Can you talk about that and
how the efforts you're doing

00:43:33.130 --> 00:43:34.690
are bringing money
to the communities

00:43:34.690 --> 00:43:38.878
or what's paying for
the schools, all that?

00:43:38.878 --> 00:43:41.490
JOHN BATTELLE: From a
technology standpoint,

00:43:41.490 --> 00:43:46.860
there's a lot going on from
education, family planning,

00:43:46.860 --> 00:43:48.710
really, really critical
components that

00:43:48.710 --> 00:43:51.810
come through the process of
using technology-- education,

00:43:51.810 --> 00:43:55.250
lights, laptops, education
centers, and so forth.

00:43:55.250 --> 00:43:56.940
What we have found
is there are so

00:43:56.940 --> 00:43:58.204
many little examples of this.

00:43:58.204 --> 00:43:59.870
On the biggest scale,
obviously everyone

00:43:59.870 --> 00:44:01.937
has always talked
about ecotourism.

00:44:01.937 --> 00:44:03.520
You bring wildlife,
you build a lodge,

00:44:03.520 --> 00:44:05.220
that's an incredible thing.

00:44:05.220 --> 00:44:08.400
That's a simple one in
terms of understanding.

00:44:08.400 --> 00:44:10.300
In terms of pastoral
communities,

00:44:10.300 --> 00:44:13.670
you have obviously cattle
and those kind of components

00:44:13.670 --> 00:44:15.220
that are really,
really critical.

00:44:15.220 --> 00:44:16.720
There are a lot of
programs going on

00:44:16.720 --> 00:44:19.610
about how to grow your own food,
how to manage your own food.

00:44:19.610 --> 00:44:22.490
We usually tie that into
the school components.

00:44:22.490 --> 00:44:25.290
GINGER THOMPSON: We have
farms at all of the schools.

00:44:25.290 --> 00:44:26.540
Not all of them have them yet.

00:44:26.540 --> 00:44:29.230
But we actually
now run 19 schools,

00:44:29.230 --> 00:44:33.250
and there are farms on I think
about 15 of the 19 schools,

00:44:33.250 --> 00:44:35.200
and they're actually
community managed.

00:44:35.200 --> 00:44:37.610
So the produce that comes
from the school farm

00:44:37.610 --> 00:44:40.660
not only feeds the
kids lunch, but also

00:44:40.660 --> 00:44:43.400
actually is sold by
community members.

00:44:43.400 --> 00:44:45.220
So it becomes a source
of income for them.

00:44:45.220 --> 00:44:47.580
So that's a piece.

00:44:47.580 --> 00:44:50.100
We have a microcredit program.

00:44:50.100 --> 00:44:52.920
And women have started, I
think, over 1,000 businesses

00:44:52.920 --> 00:44:55.780
now in Northern Kenya that
are active and thriving,

00:44:55.780 --> 00:44:57.770
and all kinds of businesses.

00:44:57.770 --> 00:45:01.510
You can explore your
imagination and probably come up

00:45:01.510 --> 00:45:02.704
with what they're doing.

00:45:02.704 --> 00:45:04.120
They're doing all
kinds of things.

00:45:04.120 --> 00:45:04.920
JOHN BATTELLE: They
have grandmothers

00:45:04.920 --> 00:45:07.730
doing sewing projects for
the schools for uniforms

00:45:07.730 --> 00:45:08.730
and so forth.

00:45:08.730 --> 00:45:10.680
So it's all very interconnected.

00:45:10.680 --> 00:45:13.570
If one community is doing
sewing of, say, uniforms,

00:45:13.570 --> 00:45:16.155
that can go across all
these different communities.

00:45:16.155 --> 00:45:19.330
GEOFFERY CHEGE: We also gave
got up to 10 water projects

00:45:19.330 --> 00:45:23.180
whereby water has been
harnessed for agriculture,

00:45:23.180 --> 00:45:26.020
that kind of farm produce.

00:45:26.020 --> 00:45:29.380
It goes toward sustaining
the family needs.

00:45:29.380 --> 00:45:31.660
And then from there, the
excess is sold to the market

00:45:31.660 --> 00:45:35.120
and brings more
cash to the family.

00:45:35.120 --> 00:45:38.260
GINGER THOMPSON: And we're doing
things like biomass stoves.

00:45:38.260 --> 00:45:42.210
We have biomass stoves in
one community as a test.

00:45:42.210 --> 00:45:45.770
And what it's doing is
basically freeing up at the time

00:45:45.770 --> 00:45:50.090
that women were spending walking
into the forest cutting limbs

00:45:50.090 --> 00:45:52.220
off trees, which we didn't
want to have happen,

00:45:52.220 --> 00:45:53.280
and then walking back.

00:45:53.280 --> 00:45:55.220
That was an eight-hour process.

00:45:55.220 --> 00:45:57.640
Now the women are
cooking at home.

00:45:57.640 --> 00:46:02.160
They manage those bio gas
stoves in about an hour a day,

00:46:02.160 --> 00:46:04.900
and they suddenly have
seven hours of free time

00:46:04.900 --> 00:46:06.660
and they're starting businesses.

00:46:06.660 --> 00:46:10.895
So each piece, each cog in the
wheel makes a big difference.

00:46:10.895 --> 00:46:12.810
JOHN BATTELLE:
It's very holistic.

00:46:12.810 --> 00:46:14.700
You can't look at
individual problems.

00:46:14.700 --> 00:46:16.212
You have to look across.

00:46:16.212 --> 00:46:17.670
You're going to
affect this region.

00:46:17.670 --> 00:46:21.490
You have to look across the
impact across multiple things.

00:46:21.490 --> 00:46:23.072
You want kids to go to school.

00:46:23.072 --> 00:46:25.530
When I started, I was like,
I'm putting power into schools.

00:46:25.530 --> 00:46:26.780
I think this is a great thing.

00:46:26.780 --> 00:46:28.080
I'm putting power into clinics.

00:46:28.080 --> 00:46:30.551
Well, if I can't feed
the child one meal a day,

00:46:30.551 --> 00:46:32.050
they're not going
to come to school.

00:46:32.050 --> 00:46:33.430
And if I can't afford
a book, they're

00:46:33.430 --> 00:46:34.340
not going to come to school.

00:46:34.340 --> 00:46:36.650
If I can't afford teachers,
I need teacher housing.

00:46:36.650 --> 00:46:39.420
So power, which is a
world that I came from,

00:46:39.420 --> 00:46:41.020
a little bit on the
technology side,

00:46:41.020 --> 00:46:42.729
I looked at like I'm
doing a great thing.

00:46:42.729 --> 00:46:44.394
And then as you get
into it, you realize

00:46:44.394 --> 00:46:46.120
that there's so many
lower elements that

00:46:46.120 --> 00:46:49.750
have to be solved in
conjunction with that problem.

00:46:49.750 --> 00:46:53.495
So it becomes pretty
powerful to engage

00:46:53.495 --> 00:46:55.120
on the ground over
there, because there

00:46:55.120 --> 00:46:56.520
are so many different levels.

00:46:56.520 --> 00:46:59.380
And the thing is, this is
what makes Lewa the anchor

00:46:59.380 --> 00:47:00.880
and the gateway to
the North for me.

00:47:00.880 --> 00:47:04.150
When I started looking at
where I can have impact,

00:47:04.150 --> 00:47:08.380
Lewa as an institution,
as a conservancy,

00:47:08.380 --> 00:47:11.440
has logistical capabilities,
they have access on the ground,

00:47:11.440 --> 00:47:13.520
they have skills,
and they have people.

00:47:13.520 --> 00:47:16.067
So when you bring an
idea to the ground,

00:47:16.067 --> 00:47:18.400
there's no better place to
develop it, test it, and move

00:47:18.400 --> 00:47:19.744
it out than Lewa.

00:47:19.744 --> 00:47:21.535
And that is why you
see those conservancies

00:47:21.535 --> 00:47:23.927
to the north developing--
because they know

00:47:23.927 --> 00:47:25.510
at the end of the
day they've got Lewa

00:47:25.510 --> 00:47:28.055
as an anchor to support
those organizations.

00:47:28.055 --> 00:47:29.600
GINGER THOMPSON:
"How can technology

00:47:29.600 --> 00:47:30.700
help with education?"

00:47:30.700 --> 00:47:33.670
We have this program
where we are currently

00:47:33.670 --> 00:47:36.760
supporting the education
of about 5,500 kids

00:47:36.760 --> 00:47:39.380
in an area around Lewa.

00:47:39.380 --> 00:47:42.390
We also have a
scholarship program

00:47:42.390 --> 00:47:46.350
that gets kids out
to secondary schools.

00:47:46.350 --> 00:47:49.120
And one, we'd like to grow that.

00:47:49.120 --> 00:47:51.260
And that actually is
something that we're

00:47:51.260 --> 00:47:53.650
going to implement
across Northern Kenya

00:47:53.650 --> 00:47:56.440
to get kids from
primary school up

00:47:56.440 --> 00:47:59.390
into secondary schools, which
is a big leap financially

00:47:59.390 --> 00:48:00.510
for the families.

00:48:00.510 --> 00:48:04.630
Primary school is free in
Kenya, but secondary school

00:48:04.630 --> 00:48:06.730
is a year's salary for somebody.

00:48:06.730 --> 00:48:11.740
So if we can get more kids
into secondary school-- and one

00:48:11.740 --> 00:48:14.420
of the ways we're thinking
of doing this is literally

00:48:14.420 --> 00:48:18.980
by starting almost like a KiVa
program that would support

00:48:18.980 --> 00:48:21.260
individual students as
they go through school.

00:48:21.260 --> 00:48:22.920
So we call it a bursary program.

00:48:22.920 --> 00:48:25.980
We have 300 kids
in it right now.

00:48:25.980 --> 00:48:28.770
And individuals like
each of us are all

00:48:28.770 --> 00:48:32.417
supporting kids in the
schools right now who

00:48:32.417 --> 00:48:34.000
are going to boarding
school, and some

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:35.670
are going to
university, and we've

00:48:35.670 --> 00:48:37.730
had graduates from medical
school this summer.

00:48:37.730 --> 00:48:39.500
It was very exciting.

00:48:39.500 --> 00:48:43.780
We want to do a lot more of
that across a greater geography.

00:48:43.780 --> 00:48:47.950
We don't have the systems in
place to really manage this.

00:48:47.950 --> 00:48:50.200
So we need help with that,
and technology could really

00:48:50.200 --> 00:48:50.817
be helpful.

00:48:50.817 --> 00:48:53.400
JOHN BATTELLE: We keep talking
about technology on the ground.

00:48:53.400 --> 00:48:54.941
But the other
component of technology

00:48:54.941 --> 00:48:58.160
that we haven't talked about
is connecting corporations,

00:48:58.160 --> 00:49:00.510
donors, and other
organizations to the efforts

00:49:00.510 --> 00:49:02.240
that are on the ground.

00:49:02.240 --> 00:49:04.789
Traditionally today, when a
donor looks at something--

00:49:04.789 --> 00:49:05.830
I want to build a school.

00:49:05.830 --> 00:49:07.314
I want to put my name on that.

00:49:07.314 --> 00:49:08.230
And we build a school.

00:49:08.230 --> 00:49:10.271
Even if we don't need it,
we will build a school.

00:49:10.271 --> 00:49:12.120
Because somebody is
going to give us money.

00:49:12.120 --> 00:49:15.110
The reality is that our
ability through technology

00:49:15.110 --> 00:49:18.240
to better connect where the
dollars need to go and better

00:49:18.240 --> 00:49:21.500
connect the donor to seeing the
work being done on the ground

00:49:21.500 --> 00:49:23.814
is a really important
next up for us so

00:49:23.814 --> 00:49:24.980
that we can more granualize.

00:49:24.980 --> 00:49:28.370
I want you to come to me and
say, I want to build a school,

00:49:28.370 --> 00:49:30.340
and I want to be able
to say within Lewa,

00:49:30.340 --> 00:49:33.284
a school is great, but here's
five things in education

00:49:33.284 --> 00:49:34.700
that are more
important, and I can

00:49:34.700 --> 00:49:36.851
keep you aware of
all these things.

00:49:36.851 --> 00:49:39.350
Because as donors, we're still
locked into brick and mortar.

00:49:39.350 --> 00:49:42.050
We're like, I want to see
something physically made

00:49:42.050 --> 00:49:43.050
that I know is there.

00:49:43.050 --> 00:49:44.630
And with technology,
we can probably

00:49:44.630 --> 00:49:46.489
break that barrier
down much better

00:49:46.489 --> 00:49:48.280
and be able to show
the impact that they're

00:49:48.280 --> 00:49:50.140
giving on a much
more granular level.

00:49:50.140 --> 00:49:52.040
And we haven't actually
begun to do that yet.

00:49:52.040 --> 00:49:52.980
GINGER THOMPSON: Yeah.

00:49:52.980 --> 00:49:55.310
And that's where things
like power comes in.

00:49:55.310 --> 00:49:58.130
If we can get power up to some
of these remote communities,

00:49:58.130 --> 00:50:01.900
we can get kids on some
kind of device and learning.

00:50:01.900 --> 00:50:04.845
And we had one child who
we were able to furnish

00:50:04.845 --> 00:50:07.730
his house with a solar light.

00:50:07.730 --> 00:50:11.370
And as a result, he was able
to do his homework at home,

00:50:11.370 --> 00:50:14.020
and he ended up getting
into Nairobi University,

00:50:14.020 --> 00:50:18.040
and he's now doing really
well in a Ph.D. program.

00:50:18.040 --> 00:50:19.620
This was a few years ago.

00:50:19.620 --> 00:50:21.470
It was tough to get
him enough power

00:50:21.470 --> 00:50:24.200
to do his homework at night so
he could qualify in the state

00:50:24.200 --> 00:50:26.830
exams to get into university.

00:50:26.830 --> 00:50:27.800
But it is happening.

00:50:27.800 --> 00:50:30.500
And these are small
steps we're making.

00:50:30.500 --> 00:50:33.190
With support, we
can go the distance.

00:50:33.190 --> 00:50:34.170
We really can.

00:50:34.170 --> 00:50:36.020
And I think what
John was saying is

00:50:36.020 --> 00:50:40.810
Lewa is really well positioned
where financial efficacy is

00:50:40.810 --> 00:50:42.570
top notch.

00:50:42.570 --> 00:50:45.120
It's why Sabrina, my colleague
who's in the back there,

00:50:45.120 --> 00:50:46.340
and I really got involved.

00:50:46.340 --> 00:50:48.339
Because we saw what was
going on and we thought,

00:50:48.339 --> 00:50:51.520
wow, this is an
amazing organization.

00:50:51.520 --> 00:50:56.060
The investment here, the very
small amount of investment--

00:50:56.060 --> 00:50:58.830
we run this whole thing on
$3 and 1/2 million a year.

00:50:58.830 --> 00:51:00.970
It's really extraordinary.

00:51:00.970 --> 00:51:03.120
That includes four
health clinics

00:51:03.120 --> 00:51:05.830
that serve 60,000 people,
these schools that

00:51:05.830 --> 00:51:09.620
are serving 5,500 kids, the
microcredit, all this stuff.

00:51:09.620 --> 00:51:14.310
It's an amazing anchor
for what can happen.

00:51:14.310 --> 00:51:15.830
And we're well poised.

00:51:15.830 --> 00:51:17.280
We're well managed.

00:51:17.280 --> 00:51:20.810
It's very well organized to
really go a big distance.

00:51:20.810 --> 00:51:24.440
